      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my blueberry bushes are turning kinda yellow lately. i dont know if the soil is too alkaline or if they just need more nitrogen. any idea how to tell the difference?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yellowing blueberry bushes can be a sign of a few different things, like an imbalance in the soil's pH or a nitrogen deficiency. You can try to check the soil, but be careful, or you might get a bad reading. A good way to start is to look at the soil itself, though, and remember that soil is just one part of the puzzle.\n\nIf the soil is too alkaline, the roots can't properly absorb nutrients, and the leaves will show symptoms. A quick, low-cost way to check for general nutrient issues is to look at the leaves closely. Are the yellowing spots starting on the older leaves first, or are the new growth also affected?\n\nA good approach is to get a soil test done. That will tell you exactly what your soil is lacking, whether it's nitrogen, phosphorus, or something else entirely. A soil test is the best way to know if you need to adjust the soil chemistry.",
