    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "the yellowing seems to be mostly on the older leaves lower down on the bush. i thought blueberries liked acidic soil right? if the pH is too high, does that mean the nitrogen is just stuck in the ground or what? i'm worried something is messing with the roots under the surface.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Blueberries absolutely thrive in acidic soil, and you are spot on about that! If the pH is too high—meaning the soil is too alkaline—it can absolutely lock up nutrients like nitrogen, making them unavailable to the roots. The nitrogen isn't necessarily \"stuck,\" but the soil chemistry is creating a barrier, so the roots can't pull it up, even if it's present.\n\nWhen the yellowing is concentrated on the older, lower leaves, that's a classic sign of a nutrient deficiency or a pH issue, because the plant prioritizes feeding the new growth. It's a sign the old, established parts are struggling to get what they need.\n\nIf you suspect the pH is the culprit, you'll need to lower it. You can do this by incorporating elemental sulfur into the soil, which slowly lowers the pH over time. It's a slow process, though, and you need patience.",
      "source": "target",
