    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "sulfur sounds like a lot of work... is there anything else that could be causing this? i noticed the soil looks a bit disturbed around the base of the plants, like something has been scratching around in the dirt lately. could it be pests or something living in the soil messing with the root system?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Disturbed soil around the base of your bushes is a big red flag, and you should definitely be looking for potential culprits! That scratching you noticed could be anything from burrowing pests to just some clumsy digging by a creature that doesn't appreciate the delicate root structure.\n\nYou might be dealing with grubs, or perhaps some kind of soil-dwelling beetle or even a particularly aggressive earthworm population. These critters can chew on the fine feeder roots, making it impossible for the blueberry bushes to absorb water and nutrients, which would certainly cause those lower leaves to yellow.\n\nIf you suspect pests, you should look for signs like small, white, grub-like larvae near the roots, or tell-tale signs of root damage—some roots might look frayed or mushy. A good way to check is to gently dig a small sample near the affected area.",
